Integrating Guava's RateLimiter with Virtual Threads is a "pro move." While a Semaphore limits how many threads can run at once,
a RateLimiter limits how fast they can execute over time (e.g., exactly 100 requests per second).
This is crucial for Salesforce, which has strict rolling window limits.
The "Throttled" Orchestrator
In this design, we will spawn 20 virtual threads (one for each batch of 100), 
but we will tell those threads to "check in" with the RateLimiter before they actually hit the Salesforce API.

import com.google.common.collect.Lists;
import com.google.common.util.concurrent.RateLimiter;
import org.springframework.stereotype.Service;

import java.util.ArrayList;
import java.util.List;
import java.util.concurrent.Callable;
import java.util.concurrent.Executors;
import java.util.concurrent.Future;

@Service
public class ThrottledSalesforceOrchestrator {

    private final SalesforceIntegrationService salesforceService;
    
    // Allow exactly 2.0 permits per second. 
    // If each batch is 100 records, this effectively limits us to 200 records/sec.
    private final RateLimiter throttler = RateLimiter.create(2.0);

    public ThrottledSalesforceOrchestrator(SalesforceIntegrationService salesforceService) {
        this.salesforceService = salesforceService;
    }

    public void processWithRateLimit(List<SalesforceRecord> allRecords) {
        List<List<SalesforceRecord>> batches = Lists.partition(allRecords, 100);

        try (var executor = Executors.newVirtualThreadPerTaskExecutor()) {
            
            List<Callable<List<SyncResult>>> tasks = batches.stream()
                .map(batch -> (Callable<List<SyncResult>>) () -> {
                    
                    // --- The Magic Line ---
                    // This blocks the virtual thread until the rate limiter allows it.
                    // Because it's a virtual thread, the underlying OS thread is freed!
                    double waitTime = throttler.acquire(); 
                    
                    if (waitTime > 0) {
                        System.out.println("Throttling: Waited " + waitTime + "s to stay within limits.");
                    }

                    return salesforceService.pushBatchToSalesforce(batch);
                })
                .toList();

            List<Future<List<SyncResult>>> futures = executor.invokeAll(tasks);
            
            // Collect and handle results...
            for (Future<List<SyncResult>> f : futures) {
                System.out.println("Batch completed with " + f.get().size() + " results.");
            }

        } catch (Exception e) {
            e.printStackTrace();
        }
    }
}

Why this is better than a Thread.sleep()
 * Smooth Distribution: If you ask for 2 requests per second, Guava doesn't wait 1 second and fire 2. It tracks time at the millisecond level and lets one through every 500ms. This prevents "bursting" that can trigger API firewalls.
 * Virtual Thread Efficiency: When throttler.acquire() causes a wait, the JVM sees the virtual thread is "waiting." It unmounts it from the CPU, letting other tasks run.
 * Adaptive: If the Salesforce API starts responding slowly, the RateLimiter still ensures you don't pile up more requests than the system can handle.
